author: @trishasuttles
text:
I don't think it was wise to do this in front of the press, especially considering the fact that 75% of the idiot journalist there are more worried about, "what ifs" or asking questions meant to instigate conflict. Another thing, I feel Zelenski strongly underestimate Trump, what he fails to realize is that what Trump is saying is that if they make a deal, and Putin violates it, Trump will take it personally, he will not allow Putin to break treaty because he will bring hell to Russia. That's what Zelenski fails to realize and what many fail to realize. It's EXACTLY what JD Vance was saying when he said that it's not what America says, it's what America does. The last president was all talk, no action. This president will attempt to talk first, but once he feels talking isn't working, he will take action, and I don't mean sanctions. I BELIEVE in my president, and I know that Putin does not underestimate My president, he's mentioned many times Trump is unpredictable. He knows that Trump will send an air strike while taking a shit in the oval toilet. Just like he did in Syria when they were using chemical weapons on civilians. Zelenski should be more respectful, 100%, he needs to comprehend that this is a new administration, this administration has balls, and a damn back bone. Now he was starting to get a bit demanding and disrespectful with the last administration making demands and shit, it's not going to fly with this administration. Trump is right, attitudes need to change and frankly, as a leader of a nation, I think it's very unprofessional and poor example of leadership on Zelenski's part to put emotions before logic. He's got an emotional hateful attitude right now which is blocking him from thinking with logic. He's blood thirsty craving revenge, he's not willing to compromise or anything
Whether or not Russia was wrong for what they did is completely beside the point. When you're in a losing position as a leader the lives of your people should weigh more valuable than land or boundaries. If you have to live with a new border, then that's what you have to do because for one, you're not going to win it back in battle, if that were the case, you'd have already regained your territory. If you're still controlling Kursk, then in all fairness, it's yours, just the same as any Russian controlled part of Ukraine. This is what happens in war. Period. It's not something new, to be unwilling to agree you this makes you an idiot and very poor selfish leader. I think that it will be tough for Ukrainians that are in those regions, but they will live, and they will have an opportunity to adjust or build new lives, that's a hell of a lot better than them losing their own lives or more loved ones. With the attitude Zelenski has right now, it appears he is determined to continue fighting Russia until he's killed his entire population. That's stupid, and poor leadership.

text:
....This message comes from a Swedish psychologist, P. WirsÃ©n. I couldn't resist sharing his words about the meeting between Zelensky and Trump. It is very important to understand this. So, read this: "It became painfully clear what narcissistic power games and psychopathology look like when Trump openly humiliated Zelensky at the White House. In front of recognized journalists from around the world, he called Zelensky "disrespectful," questioned his loyalty, and insinuated that he did not deserve support from the United States. As if that were not enough, he warned that Zelensky could cause a third world warâ€”a classic psychopathic trait where threats are used as a means to gain control.

It was not just a sign of poor diplomacy; it was a demonstrative manifestation of power, marked by narcissism and psychopathy.

ğŸ”¹ Grandiose self-image and need for submission
â€” Trump expected Zelensky to show gratitude and admiration. When that did not happen, he publicly punished him. People with narcissistic personality disorder cannot tolerate their self-image being questioned and use humiliation as a defense.

ğŸ”¹Manipulation and threats
â€” Blaming someone for a potential disaster is a classic psychopathic tactic. By saying that Zelensky is "playing with World War III," he shifts the blame onto him while portraying himself as the only one who can prevent the catastrophe.

ğŸ”¹ Impulsive and emotionally driven exertion of power
â€” When Trump felt challenged by Zelensky, he abruptly ended the meeting. A stable and strategic leader would have handled the situation diplomatically, but someone with psychopathic traits instinctively reacts based on their sense of losing control.

But why did he do this in front of the press? This is why narcissists and psychopaths love to display their power publicly. By humiliating Zelensky before the eyes of the world, he not only sends a message to him but to all leaders and nations: "I am the one who decides, and those who disobey will be crushed."

What we witnessed was not just a president behaving inappropriately. It was a textbook example of how narcissistic and psychopathic leaders use humiliation, threats, and manipulation to assert their power. And just like in destructive relationships, this is never about building but about controlling.

And why was the agreement about minerals? What is needed to drive a Tesla? Narcissists, dictators, and psychopaths idealize each other and scratch each other's backs in unholy alliances.

Trump can no longer claim to be the leader of the free world. His actions today do not place him among democratic statesmen but among the dictators of history. A true leader builds alliances through respect and diplomacy, while a dictator rules through threats, fear, and humiliation. When the fate of the world is at stake, we must not close our eyes to the difference.
That day [28 Feb 2025], we did not see a president; we saw a full-fledged despot."

text:
Even in the case of terrorists, the basic principles of international humanitarian law apply, and exceptions regarding the protection of wounded and unarmed individuals are not permitted. If terrorists are involved in an armed conflict, they are subject to the same international legal protections as other combatants. This means:

1. Dignity and Humane Treatment: Even if a person is considered a terrorist, they must not be treated inhumanely if they are wounded, unarmed, or captured. They are entitled to humane treatment under the Geneva Conventions.
2. Rule of Law: Terrorists are also entitled to a fair trial and cannot be killed or mistreated outside of legal processes. States are not allowed to arbitrarily bypass international humanitarian law.
3. Prohibition of Torture and Extrajudicial Killings: The Geneva Conventions and other international legal standards, such as the Convention Against Torture, prohibit any form of torture, inhumane treatment, or extrajudicial executions, regardless of whether the individual is a terrorist.

In conclusion: While terrorism is a serious threat, the rules of international humanitarian law and human rights must still be respected in the fight against terrorism. Exceptions or deviations from these principles are not allowed. Human rights and the right to a fair trial apply to all individuals, regardless of their actions.
